Use this toolset to investigate issues using Jira and Confluence (Atlassian suite).

**Jira — issue queries (JQL):**
- Always prefer JQL for Jira searches — it is the most powerful and precise query method
- Example: `project = OPS AND issuetype = Incident AND status != Done AND created >= -7d ORDER BY created DESC`
- Filter by label: `labels = "payment-service"`
- Filter by component: `component = "checkout-api"`
- Filter by priority: `priority in (Critical, High)`
- Filter by assignee: `assignee = currentUser()` or `assignee = "user@company.com"`
- Filter by fix version: `fixVersion = "2024.Q4.1"`
- Full-text search: `text ~ "database connection timeout"`

**Jira — common investigation patterns:**
- Find open incidents for a service: `project = OPS AND issuetype = Incident AND labels = "<service-name>" AND status != Done`
- Find recently closed incidents: `project = OPS AND issuetype = Incident AND status = Done AND resolved >= -24h`
- Find related bugs: `project = <project> AND issuetype = Bug AND component = "<component>" AND status != Done`
- Find work linked to a deployment: `fixVersion = "<version>" AND status != Done`

**Confluence — page search:**
- Search for runbooks: use CQL `space = OPS AND label = "runbook" AND title ~ "<service-name>"`
- Search by text content: `text ~ "incident response" AND space = OPS`
- Fetch a specific page by ID when you have the URL (extract the numeric ID from the URL path)
- Always use `expand=body.storage` when fetching page content to get the full text

**Cross-referencing Jira and Confluence:**
- When investigating an incident, search Confluence for runbooks related to the affected service
- Check Jira for previous incidents with the same symptoms to find known solutions
- Look for post-mortem documents in Confluence linked to similar past incidents

**Best practices:**
- Scope JQL queries to specific projects to avoid searching the entire Jira instance
- Use `maxResults=20` to limit response size — increase only if needed
- When a Jira issue has a Confluence page linked, fetch that page for additional context
- Check the `comment` field on Jira issues for investigation notes from previous responders
